<font color="#FF0000">A PHONE CALL</font><br>
<tt>Thu Nov 13  1:41:09 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Veterans Day 1997 and a special event that happened to me.<br><br>
 During the years since my return for 'Nam I have had my share of those unkind people who's comments AND actions <br>
made me more than mad, I think all Veterans , Nam and others have had this type thing happen .. nothing new really. We <br>
Vietnam Vet's have had it happen a little more than others it is safe to say but that is not the point. Point is that it would be easy to single out those events<br>
and dwell on them and let the rage build within feeling put upon by the WHOLE world... Not so.<br><br>
 Nov 11th 1997 @18:30 hrs my phone rings and it is a good friend of mine who used to work for the same company I do. It's a friend and after a few opening exchanges he gets right to the point of his call ( I hope I can remember it exactly )<br><br>
  &quot; I just call to tell you that I was thinking of you and of all the vet's today and I wanted to just say.. Thank You.. that's all. &quot;<br><br>
 I knew what he was driving at in an instant, thanking me for my service to this GREAT country of ours.. and that he had been thinking of ALL VETERANS on this day. It is hard to express the feelings of how humble this old grunt felt after a comment like that, how his Thank You loomed as such a powerful expression of HIS love for this country, expression of gratitude toward all vet's . <br><br>
 While we worked for the same company he would from time to time ask me questions about my time in 'Nam and with a HUGE difference from other people.... He TRULY LISTENED.<br><br>
No excusses, no comments .. he listened to what a vet had to say. Too young at the time to serve in 'Nam himself.. but here is someone who is NOT bashing Vietnam Veterans, or<br>
ANY VETERANS... Someone who does not call me baby-burner and worse, someone who cares what WE veterans did for our country. Like I said it all too easy to focus on those<br>
who would throw rocks at Vets and sometimes I have lost sight that there are people in this world like him. For this old grunt this is a case where one at' a boy wiped out 10 thousand aw sh*t's or more exactly one simple Thank You overshadows 10 million baby-burner comments.<br><br>
It is hard to express how that lifted my mood on a day when heavy thoughts and sadness can so easy take over ones day. I wish that EVERY 'Nam vet would get a phone call like that, that a healing event that would be for both, that a healing for OUR country that would be. Maybe this kind of thing happens all the time but I doubt it..and I just don't know it, but what if....<br><br>
  My Friend Lee, I will be proud to stand side by side with you as the parade passes by and we both show our respects to the passing flag. Hold your head as high and proud as I do for our flag &amp; country.  NEVER feel you have done little for this country, for if you have done so for the least of veterans, me , you have done so for ALL Veterans. This little note in the Vietnam Veterans web page is a tribute to just such actions and this humble grunts way of telling you.... <br><br>
          You are very welcome.<br><br>
Gary 'J.'<br>
Co B 1/327 Inf 101St ABN '68-71<br><br>

<p><code>--   (Gary 'J.') </code><p>


